      "type": "Annotation",
      "motivation": [
        "supplementing",
        "commenting"
      ],
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": " Well, I don't really want to add to the sufferings of the audience in this thing. When I say Kafka is an allegory, I don't mean that I don't like allegories. And in particular I don't mean that I don't like Kafka, whose work I know very well and admire enormously. I do feel all the time that when people start discussing things like the novel and the short story, they ought merely for the purpose of discussion to define the term precisely. It doesn't matter whether they're defining it accurately or not.",
          "format": "text/plain",
          "purpose": "commenting"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "Frank O'Connor",
          "format": "text/plain",
          "purpose": "tagging"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "August 5 Session Discussion",
          "format": "text/plain",
          "purpose": "tagging"
        }
      ],
      "target": {
        "source": {
          "id": "https://tanyaclement.github.io/harvard1953/august-5-afternoon-part-three/canvas-1/canvas",
          "type": "Canvas",
          "partOf": [
